						<!---Each one of these sections can be used as a separate blog post.--->
						<div id="content" class="8u skel-cell-important">
							<section>
								<header>
									<h2>Bonsai Bubble : SteelHacks 2016</h2>
									<span class="byline">Spring 2016 [Written on 10-16-2016]</span>
								</header>
								<p><a href="#" class="image full"><img src="../../images/BonsaiBubble.jpg" alt=""></a></p>
								<p>SteelHacks is the largest and only MLH sanctioned hackathon in the Western PA area, and it is relatively young (2 yrs old) compared to other major hackathons. In February of 2016, Design Hub organized a small group of interested club members and split into two teams to work on a hack for the next 36 hrs. </p>
								<p>I worked with Michael Adams (soph BioE) and Katrina Haidari (soph MechE) on a physical Bonsai plant enclosure that was designed to maintain constant temperature and humidity in the dorm room environment by sensing and responding to the external environment. We used a Raspberry PI 2 with temperature and humidity sensors to read and process the data, and applied the Twython API to give regular status updates via our Bonsai plant's personalized Twitter account. </p>

								<p>It's worth noting that we initially wanted to work on a healthcare hack however we weren't able to come up with anything that we considered worth working on that was also within the scope of our limited abilities. At the time, Michael and I were first-time hackathon participants and all three of us were only capable of basic programming in C++ and Matlab. Bonsai Bubble originated from an offhand comment by Michael about how difficult it was to maintain his personal Bonsai tree in college dorms (which are apparently stressful environments). The project quickly got off the ground from there, and our efforts were later recognized as we ended up in the top 10 projects at SteelHacks 2016.</p>

								<p>Hackathons are typically events that people stereotype with computer science students coding furiously at their computers. That's starting to change, but I could definitely see where it originated, after taking a good look around me. When we started constructing our physical enclosure for the Bonsai Bubble (PVC and a plastic wrap with less elasticity than saran wrap), people often took breaks from their work to ask us what we were working on. The idea of a physical prototype seemed completely foreign to many of the people I interacted with, but it was clear from the other top projects, that they were not only helpful, but critical in sharing the user experience, and in sharing a story, with the judges and other hackers at the event. </p>
							
							</section>
						</div>

